\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 	Man Pages\

\f1\b0\fs16 \
\pard\tx532\tx1065\tx1601\tx2135\tx2667\tx3202\tx3736\tx4270\tx4802\tx5337\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Man pages can be opened by title, the same as using the command-line \'91man\'92 command, or by opening a file from the file system.  To open a page by its title, use the \'93Open Title\'85\'94 menu item and enter in the name.\
\
Man pages are organized by type into \'93sections\'94.  For example, user command-line programs are in section 1, so \'91man(1)\'92 refers to the command-line man program, \'91printf(1)\'92 to the \'93printf\'94 program, and \'91printf(3)\'92 to the printf() function in the programmer libraries (since section 3 is for standard library routines).  Normally, all sections are searched for a title, with the first one found being displayed.  If a particular manual section is desired, the popup on Open Title panel can be used or it can be typed in manually between parentheses (i.e. \'93printf(3)\'94) or before the name as on the command line (\'933 printf\'94).  A typed-in section will override the popup.\
\
When Open is chosen on the Open Titles panel, the actual man(1) program is used to generate the page, with the results being displayed in a new man page window.  If multiple words are entered, a man page window will be opened for each word.\
\
An explicit man page file (included gzipped man files) can be opened using the standard file panel, available from the \'93Open File\'85\'94 menu item.  If the file appears to be nroff(1) source, the Nroff command as specified in the preferences is used to format it, otherwise it is assumed the file is pre-formatted.  The results are displayed in a man page window.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 	Man Page Window
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
The man page window simply shows the contents of the manual page, or a brief message if it was not found.  If a section of text is highlighted, pressing the Open Selection button at the top right of the window will cause each \'93word\'94 in the selection to be opened as a title (sections names in parentheses should be automatically recognized, even if there is a space between the title and section).  This can be useful to open an entire series of pages at once, particularly from the \'93SEE ALSO\'94 area of manual pages.\
\
There is a \'93Section:\'94 pulldown in the toolbar area that has a list of the section headers within that man page (if ManOpen can figure them out at least).  Choosing one of those headers will jump to that section.\
\
Any piece of text that appears to be a reference to another man page will be hyperlinked, and clicking on the hyperlink will open that page in a new document.   Note that referenced pages sometimes do not actually exist, though this should be rare.  Also, in some cases special formatting characters present in the raw man page can confuse the hyperlinking feature, meaning a page reference that looks like it should be hyperlinked isn\'92t.  In this case, use the Open Selection button.  The space bar can be used to page down, and shift-space pages up.\
\
The find panel can be used to search for text in the window, and the contents can be printed.  The default size for a window can be set to the current window\'92s size with the \'93Set Default Windows Size\'94 menu item.\
\pard\tx532\tx1065\tx1601\tx2135\tx2667\tx3202\tx3736\tx4270\tx4802\tx5337\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

