\cf0 	Apropos
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Apropos(1) (or the \'93man -k\'94 command) is essentially a basic search mechanism for man pages.  From the \'93Apropos\'85\'94 panel a string can be entered, and all man pages whose name or synopsis line contains the string will be displayed in a new window.  A cute side effect is that if no string is entered, a list of all man pages on the system will be displayed.\
\
In the list window, double-clicking on an item will open that manual page.\
\
If this feature never seems to find any results, it\'92s possible that the man page database that apropos(1) uses has not been generated.  The database is normally regenerated every week very early on Saturday mornings, but if there has been a recent problem or you\'92ve never left your machine running overnight on Fridays, it\'92s possible this is the problem.  To regenerate the database, either run the \'93/usr/libexec/makewhatis\'94 program when logged on as the root user (or \'93sudo /usr/libexec/makewhatis\'94 when logged on as an admin user), or run the full weekly maintenance scripts by running \'93sudo /etc/weekly\'94.  Of course, you could also just make sure to leave your machine running overnight between Friday/Saturday :-)  \
\

\f0\b\fs28 	Preferences
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
ManOpen has a few preference settings.  There are some basic formatting options for displayed man pages, an option to automatically exit the app when the list window is closed, options to keep the Open Title and Apropos panels open after opening a selection, and an option to open the Open Title panel upon startup.\
\
The font used for display can be set.  For best results, this should be a fixed-width font such as Monaco or Courier.  Note that if the chosen font doesn\'92t have bold and/or italic versions (such as Monaco), then any bold/italic formatting will not show up.\
\
The background color, text color, and link color can be set. \
\
The nroff formatting command used for opening nroff-source files can be specified.  By default, this is set to the same command that man(1) uses internally.  This is meant for people who have installed other nroff formatting packages on their system and want to use them instead; otherwise this setting should be left alone.  A '%@' in the string will be replaced by the filename.\
\
Finally, the list of paths searched for manual pages can be specified.  By default, these are the standard system path plus the typical path for third-party pages; more paths can be added if necessary.  Drag and drop to change the order of the path, and use the \'93+\'94 button or drag folders from Finder to add more.  Copy and paste of colon-separated paths is also supported. These paths will be passed to the man(1) command using the -M flag.\
\pard\tx532\tx1065\tx1601\tx2135\tx2667\tx3202\tx3736\tx4270\tx4802\tx5337\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
ManOpen supports the \'93x-man-page\'94 URL scheme that was introduced by Apple in Mac OS X 10.3 (Panther), where Terminal.app handles it by invoking man(1) in a new window.  This is used when hyperlinks like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "x-man-page://ls"}}{\fldrslt x-man-page://ls}} are opened.  ManOpen also supports this scheme by opening a new window.  It also includes a preference to set the default application, similar to the Web Browser preference in Safari.app.  If this isn\'92t changed, Terminal.app will continue to be the application used.\
\
