\cf0 There is an \'93openman\'94 command-line tool provided in this package.  This has a syntax similar to the man(1) command, but it messages the ManOpen application to display the pages there.  To install the tool, put it somewhere in the standard Unix $PATH, such as /usr/local/bin.  It is further documented in its man page.\
\
Starting with Mac OS X 10.2, /usr/local/bin is no longer in the default $PATH, so you\'92ll need to add it yourself.  If you use tcsh, in your ~/.[t]cshrc file, add the line:\
\
\pard\tx532\tx1065\tx1601\tx2135\tx2667\tx3202\tx3736\tx4270\tx4802\tx5337\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 	set path = (/usr/local/bin $path)\
\pard\tx532\tx1065\tx1601\tx2135\tx2667\tx3202\tx3736\tx4270\tx4802\tx5337\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf0 \
If you use tcsh as your shell, you can set openman\'92s completion settings to be similar to man(1)\'92s, which causes it to complete using command name.  Add the following to your ~/.cshrc or ~/.tchrc:\
\
\pard\tx532\tx1065\tx1601\tx2135\tx2667\tx3202\tx3736\tx4270\tx4802\tx5337\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 	complete openman 'n/-M/d/' 'p/*/c/'\
\pard\tx532\tx1065\tx1601\tx2135\tx2667\tx3202\tx3736\tx4270\tx4802\tx5337\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf0 \
Starting with Mac OS X 10.2, the completion for man(1) isn\'92t set up by default.  You can add a similar entry for \'91man\'92, or look at the files in /usr/share/tcsh/examples to re-enable the old default setup.\
\
For bash(1) users, you can get nearly the same behavior.  Add the following to ~/.bashrc:\
\
\pard\tx532\tx1065\tx1601\tx2135\tx2667\tx3202\tx3736\tx4270\tx4802\tx5337\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f2 \cf0 	complete -c openman\
